	<td class="alt1">
	
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>Community in WoW.</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#330066" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>I have been wondering a bit about what the experienced beta players and other people who like to BS about MMOGs think about the community that will develop in WoW.<br />
<br />
I have been hearing a lot about fast-paced, low downtime action.  A lot about soloing.  And a lot about groups that last only very short times to meet quest objectives and then breaking up.  That sounded great when I first heard about it, but then I started thinking about the online games I have played a lot.<br />
<br />
The tightest community I have ever experienced in a game are my friends and guildies in EQ.  When I think about how I met these people, most of them started with a couple long xp group sessions together, with chatter during downtimes.<br />
<br />
When I played Asheron's Call, a game that had little grouping and almose zero downtime, I had some friends and a guild.  But it was not nearly as close as my EQ friends are.  <br />
<br />
Now, this isn't an issue for people who come to the game with a guild.  But for people starting out in WoW, will they make friends as easily or as well in a game with short, no downtime groups?  The &quot;antigrinding&quot; code adds to this concern a little, but the concern has always been there (I don't want this to turn into yet another fatigue thread!)<br />
<br />
This is more of a &quot;maybe the things we hate about EQ are the things that enabled us to make friends in EQ&quot; thread.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
