<div>Join Date: Apr 2004</div>
				
				<div>
					
					
				</div>
				<div>   </div>
			</div>					
		
	</td>
	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>I've wondered myself how the increased pace will affect community.<br />
<br />
In general, I figure it'll be alot of freedom.  People don't <i>have</i> to group, and 'perfect' groups don't <i>have</i> to stay together.  I think this gives groups more meaning in general - since there's little penalty to leaving a group simply because you don't like the other members so much.<br />
<br />
If I could draw a bad analogy, EQ is much like school, or work.  It locks everyone into the same situations for hours on end, day after day.  You pretty much have no choice to opt-out of interacting with the people around you.  In EQ, you pretty much <i>have</i> to adventure within your peer group (those of same level), and you certainly don't want to leave a functioning group just because one of the members is annoying.  <br />
<br />
Sure, friendships form - but so does friction between 'cliques'.  It's truly eerie how much EQ's community resembles high-school social dynamics, or corporate politics.<br />
<br />
WoW is more like meeting people in your free time (imagine that, entertainment that functions like entertainment).  If you're (for instance) at a bar and it's not what you consider a 'fun' time, you simply leave.  Nothing's keeping you there - nothing's forcing you to cooperate with the people around you.  If you just want to play pool and have a few beers - there's other places to do that.  <br />
<br />
You may not be pressed into meeting as many people, but overall, the majority of your extended encounters are positive.  Sure, there's friction - but it's entirely <i>optional</i>.  If you get sick of the same-old crowd, or risking running into an Ex, you go to a different place.<br />
<br />
I expect that the community in WoW has a better chance of becoming a healthy, positive place.  Easing the contention for scarce content (e.g. none of EQ's rare spawns being raced for/politicized) - and easing the requirements that lock people's playtimes directly to the level-range of those around them make for a more fluid environment.<br />
<br />
Of course, there's little, right now, that supports the coordinated efforts of 'friends of friends'.  The trick to preventing the community from remaining small groups of strangers - is to create purposes for guilds, and to keep guild sizes relatively high.  <br />
<br />
One of which seems to be done (10+ for a guild), and the other (guild raid content) is supposedly on the schedule.  So I'm still optimistic.<br />
<br />
It's pretty easy to remember a community fondly when we're removed from the social friction that went along with it.  EQ's design certainly helped people make friends - but it also created the undesireable types of social encounters.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
