	</table>
</div><br />
Frankly, if you want to play a single player game, there are many other alternatives that are more appealing from a graphical perspective and have better, more original challenges. EverQuest is a massively multiplayer online role playing game -- it is meant to be played with others, and like massively multiplayer online role playing games should be, is meant to be completed with the assistance of others. If you want to solo, or want a &quot;solitary&quot; experience in a MMOG, take a look at Star Wars Galaxies. Having played it myself, virtually all of the major problems -- &quot;balance&quot; issues aside -- stem from the fact that the game is soloable, by and large.<br />
<br />
EverQuest's biggest drive is ultimately the reason why so many people cite their lack of contentment with it: it is highly competitive, and pits players against one another for the acquisition of game items and completion of game objectives, while at the same time promising them the unattainable goal of becoming a &quot;hero&quot; in a game world with thousands of &quot;heroes&quot;. This isn't a game for people who want communist-style hand-outs; it's a game for people who get what they put into it, and understand that, by design, they're going to have to form relationships with other players, and become antagonistic and competitive towards other players.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
