	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				And is grouping the only way to be social in a MMORPG? This concept of &quot;if you want to solo hunt, play a single player game&quot; is just rather stupid/ignorant statement.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div><br />
Hardly. In games, you want people to play with one another in order to encourage meaningful social connections in the game world. Otherwise, you're essentially just making friends in chat rooms -- and, frankly, there are much nicer chat rooms than EverQuest (Graffe's IRC Channel included) for making friends at random. The key thing here is to make friends, within the game, based upon what you do in the game. Growing interdependence among characters is the biggest single contributor to the creation of a long-lasting and viable community base. Consider games like Diablo, where grouping has never been a prerequisite. There are few, if any, sites like Graffe's in these games because people don't need anyone else's help. They can just read spoilers and do the quests on their own. Switch the view over to Asheron's Call, EverQuest, and the new generation of MMORPGs, and you'll see the emphasis on gaming socially has been largely responsible for creating communitarian-driven web sites and groups. <br />
<br />
Again, the question I think players need to ask themselves is: &quot;Am I going to pay $15 a month to solo most of the content?&quot; The monthly subscription has to justify something more than access to pixels and automated responses -- I've always maintained that it's due to the people and the community that a profitable online enterprise gets started. As I run several subscription-based websites, I can also personally attest to the fact that no one in their right mind would pay a monthly subscription to play a MUD where they are the only player, or where they can do everything on their own. When there's interdependence and a joint-reliance upon other players, people tend to seem to understand that what they're paying for is access to a community first, and access to content second.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
